Whilst it is well-recognized that women’s bodies cannot be regarded as a man’s possession, the opposition to abortion nonetheless specifically targets a woman’s agency over her own body. This is explicitly seen in feminist discourses, where female bodies are displaced from the woman themselves and claimed by more metastatic bodies, arising from patriarchal structures such as the law. Merab Mamardashvili argued, for example, that “there is no gender-free man, because there is no gender-free society” (cited in Roth forthcoming).

Such thinking acknowledges that male bodies are also molded by oppressive institutions and held captive or forced to adhere to certain patriarchal models. However, protecting a female body from such appropriations leads to the fixation on one topography of oppression which, however relentless, is only one facet of patriarchy. In this framing, male bodies are not denied the freedom to make any decisions. It bars normative accountability in its promotion of the “purity” of women’s bodies. Indeed its logic extends beyond arguments for the enactment of abortion laws and positions itself as opposed to any platform of advocating for women’s rights. The result is that gender violence, sexualization of women’s bodies, harmful traditional practices, and sexual coercion are all seen as an individual woman’s fault, much like appendicitis, which is dismissed for “use of poor judgement,” but “no life threatening disease.”
